Fix up the data API on RouteController and fixes...

This makes the `this.data()` and this.data({title: 'example'})` api more
consistent and predictable. When you define a controller or route you can
provide a data property like this:

data: function () {
 return Items.findOne({_id: this.params._id})
}

Now, you can call this.data({...}) to set the data value at a later time, or
this.data() to get the value from inside one of your controller functions.

Fix standard hooks...

You no longer get these hooks for free. You need to ask for them. You can pass a
string name for the hook. For example:

// run the loading hook for all routes as a before hook
Router.before('loading');

// run the notFound hook for all routes as a before hook
Router.before('notFound');

Remember that the order of hooks matters. In this example, you want the notFound
hook to come last since we want to show a loading indicator until the controller
is ready. The notFound hook checks whether the data value is falsy and if so,
renders the notFound template. But we don't want to do that until the data is
actually ready!

Configure template and controller name converters...

For example:

Router.configure({
  templateNameConverter: 'class', // or 'camel'
  controllerNameConverter: function (input) {
    var output = Utils.capitalize(input);

    // note the output will still have Controller appended at the end
    // for now

    return output;
  }
});

Fixed error when collecting parent hooks

Child controller inherits prototype's methods from the parent controller prototype.

So, if we have `Parent` controller

```js
Parent.prototype.before = function () {
  console.log('parent.before');
};
```

and we create `Child` class inheriting from the `Parent` we will have prototype as follows:

```js
Child.prototype.before = function () {
  console.log('parent.before');
};
```

Now when collecting hooks, the result hooks array will contain both functions instead one and it will cause double hook execution.

The problem is this line: https://github.com/EventedMind/iron-router/blob/dev/lib/route_controller.js#L45

```js
return ctor.prototype[hookName] ? hooks.concat(ctor.prototype[hookName]) : hooks;
```

What it does is checking if given hook is in the given prototype but it will be true even if the hook is not in the prototype. It's because it will look in the prototype of the parent class and so on. So, if we have three classes inheriting from each other:

`C` <- `B` <- `A` <- `RouteController`

and only `A` class will have `after` or `before` hook, it will still think that each one has given hook.

To deal with that, we have to explicitly check if a given prototype has a hook by using `Utils.hasOwnProperty` function.

```js
return Utils.hasOwnProperty(ctor.prototype, hookName) ? hooks.concat(ctor.prototype[hookName]) : hooks;
```

WIP - New rendering component for the router.

cc @tmeasday, @piffie, @warsamebashir, @richiebe, @CMToups, @ryw, @eichie,
@payner35, @gabrielhpugliese.

- Doesn't work yet but I wanted to push and get feedback
- The idea is that the Router has a _renderer instance
- This _renderer is responsible for tracking a layout, a data context and one or
  more templates to be rendered into named yields. Each can vary independently.

Benefits:
 - @piffie's idea to allow recursive yields into child templates
 - controller level layouts
 - data context can be preserved across routes
 - templates and layouts can change independently

Example using the raw RouterRenderer:

```javascript
var renderer = new RouterRenderer;
document.body.appendChild(renderer.render());
renderer.setLayout('layout');
renderer.setTemplate('mainTemplate'); // render to __main__ region
renderer.setTemplate('asideTemplate', 'aside'); // {{yield 'aside'}}
renderer.setTemplate('footerTemplate', 'footer'); // {{yield 'footer'}}
renderer.setData({title: 'Some data context'});
```
